data.event: Warren County was created by European Americans in 1807 from a portion of White County, and named for Joseph Warren (1741â€“1775), a solder in the American Revolution.
The revised Tennessee State Constitution of 1834 stated that no new county could be within 12 miles (19 km) of the county seat of the county from which it was formed.
Most saltpeter mining occurred during the War of 1812 and the Civil War.
